hands_on_practices.problem:
An isothermal, bulk free-radical polymerization (FRP) of a monovinyl monomer proceeds under steady-state with no chain transfer and negligible chain-length dependence of rate constants. Consider two limiting kinetic scenarios that differ only in the microscopic termination mode of the growing radicals: in case A, termination is exclusively by bimolecular combination; in case B, termination is exclusively by bimolecular disproportionation. Let the kinetic chain length $ ar{
u}$ be defined as the average number of propagation steps a radical executes during its lifetime, i.e., $ ar{
u} = R_p/R_i$, where $R_p$ is the rate of monomer consumption by propagation and $R_i$ is the rate at which radicals that successfully initiate growing chains enter the system. Under steady-state, the rate of radical generation equals the rate of radical loss. The number-average degree of polymerization $X_n$ is defined as the ratio of the rate of monomer consumption to the rate of formation of dead polymer molecules, and the number-average molecular weight $M_n$ satisfies $M_n = X_n M_0$, where $M_0$ is the monomer molar mass.

Starting solely from these definitions and steady-state radical balance, derive how the relationship between $M_n$ and $ ar{
u}$ depends on the termination mode (combination versus disproportionation). Then, for fixed $R_p$ (and otherwise identical conditions), compute the ratio $M_{n,\mathrm{comb}}/M_{n,\mathrm{disp}}$. Express the final ratio as a pure number (no units). No rounding is required.
